    <item>
      <title>No No No! I Got Summoned To Another World As A Demon And Now I Have To Follow Each And Every One Of Mistress&amp;#8217;s Orders!?</title>
      <author> magicswordszin </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/2128980/no-no-no-i-got-summoned-to-another-world-as-a-demon-and-now-i-have-to-follow-each-and-every-one-of-mistresss-orders/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2128980-no-no-no-i-got-summoned-to-another-world-as-a-demon-and-now-i-have-to-follow-each-and-every-one-of-mistresss-orders/chapter/2146197/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.scribblehub.com/series/2128980/no-no-no-i-got-summoned-to-another-world-as-a-demon-and-now-i-have-to-follow-each-and-every-one-of-mistresss-orders/</guid>
      <pubDate>Tue, 27 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Long ago, a war fought with demons conjured from hell nearly destroyed Tedor. In a surprising display of sense, every surviving kingdom agreed that demon-summoning was too dangerous. They sealed away the tomes and executed the summoners, and that particular sorcery was lost to time.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Clearly they didn't do a good enough job. Agnes Sloane, a 38-year old demon computer programmer, has been conjured from the region of Hell known as Seattle and forced to do the bidding of an ambitious duchess of Siteria. Desperately, Agnes clings to the hope that she someday might find a way to return to her wife and daughter.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I wouldn't hold my breath, though.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2128980-no-no-no-i-got-summoned-to-another-world-as-a-demon-and-now-i-have-to-follow-each-and-every-one-of-mistresss-orders/chapter/2146197/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Action Cat&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;I observed the distant fortress, planning my assault. As usual, I'd been given a very specific to-do list, a set of rules to precisely control my behavior, and no intel of any kind, so this kind of surveillance was important. Probably wouldn't be able to intuit where the dungeon was by which windows were lit, though. As I considered angles of approach, I reached up and fidgeted with my collar, sliding a finger under it and twisting the smooth band around my neck, like I used to do with my wedding ring.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A stealthy approach would be best. Not because Mistress had ordered me to. Actually, the fact that she hadn't probably meant that whatever machinations she had spinning were relying on me making a ruckus. No; if I was stealthy then fewer people would try to stop me and I wouldn't have to do so much killing. That's why I was taking my time surveying the place.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Currently, I was about two miles away, laying down on a hill in the twilight, using a spell that bent the air into a lens to magnify my vision. It was new — I'd learned it recently to replace the expensive spyglass that I'd broken during my last mission — and it worked better than I thought it would, though it was finicky to cast. I'd spent the past day observing my target from different angles so that I could get a complete picture. No time limit on this mission, so I was allowed to be as slow as I wanted as long as I was steadily working toward a goal.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The fort's external defenses were twofold: a broad moat and high stone walls. It was five sided, with small towers at each corner, a pretty typical configuration for a smallish Arvallan castle. I hadn't been able to get a clear view inside, but probably there were alarm bells or signal fires or something. Tonight there were only two guards patrolling the walls.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The internal keep's defenses were presumably soldier-based, which I would have no troubles with. There might be other stuff, but that would be placed to defend the minor nobles who lived here, with whom I had no business whatsoever unless they took up arms to personally defend their home. Magical defenses were unlikely for such a low-ranking family, but were never completely out of the question, especially now that Arvall's diplomatic relationships with the beastkin of Daumeir looked to be improving.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;When I used to read portal fantasy books, I would always get frustrated when the main character would totally gloss over all the worldbuilding stuff, but now I kind of get it. I can't provide a comprehensive look at the current geopolitical situation in Tedor right now, partially because I don't have a clear view of it myself and partially because I need to break into this fucking fortress, but here's a simple version. This is Arvall, fairly close to the Daumeir border. The kingdom that I'm from is Siteria, to the south. The continent that we're on is called Tedor. Okay, great, let's move on.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I said it was a moat, but I'd always pictured a moat as a fairly narrow strip of water around a castle. Really, it was more like there was an artificial lake that went right up to the castle's walls. I might be able to jump it, this body's strength meant that I could jump a ridiculously long distance, but the amount of momentum that I'd need would have me slamming into the wall like a cannonball. I could swim across, but I'd probably need to take off most of my gear. I might be ten times as strong as a normal person from this world, but I would still sink.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;After swimming across, I'd need to climb the walls. Getting climbing equipment past the moat would be tough, so the most efficient way would be to jam my clawed fingers into the mortar between the stones. That sort of thing took precision, so no enhanced speed. If I got noticed, the guards would have plenty of time to shoot arrows down at me. Or dump boiling oil on me, which wouldn't kill me but would hurt like hell. Even if they didn't notice, I'd still be clinging to the side of a sheer wall soaking wet while cold wind whipped around me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I shivered.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Or I could just kick the door down. The fort was accessible by a long bridge just wide enough for a single cart. There were two guards stationed at the land end of the bridge, equipped with spears in addition to their standard swords and breastplates. There was also a bell to ring in case of an alarm. Some nights there were one or two more guards patrolling back and forth across the bridge but not tonight for some reason. I guess I was lucky. At the fortress end of the bridge was the gatehouse. There would be at least one more guard in there, along with the typical double-portcullis meant to trap invaders.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I tried to convince myself that the only moral thing to do was to risk the moat. Except it wasn't not like this was an &lt;em&gt;assassination&lt;/em&gt;. It was a rescue, which meant that I'd need to lead an escort back out. &lt;em&gt;They&lt;/em&gt; wouldn't be able to climb down the wall and swim to shore with arrows flying after them. So I'd have to go out the front and face down the guards at the bridge anyway.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In my heart I was still a normal person, despite everything. I liked to think that I was, at least, that if I managed to make it back home my wife would still recognize me. I wasn't sure whether Mistress had chosen to let me retain my sense of morality or if she'd just been unable to change it, but even though I'd gotten somewhat desensitized to killing, I was still fucked up about getting blood on my hands.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I imagined myself as I once was, a chubby computer programmer with mousy brown hair from Washington, and couldn't help but laugh bitterly at the thought of that kind of person having a dramatic inner monologue about whether or not she'd gotten used to killing. The ridiculous nature of my situation still made me laugh. I should say, actually, that I &lt;em&gt;had&lt;/em&gt; to laugh at it, because the moment that I stopped laughing I would start screaming.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I &lt;em&gt;really&lt;/em&gt; didn't want to swim through the moat and climb the wall if there was a chance it would be for nothing. And I wasn't all that good at being sneaky anyway.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Maybe … maybe if they saw a demon approaching they would just run. If I told them how to get away from me safely. Certainly word should have spread of my exploits by now. They had to know that without specific precautions they wouldn't have any chance to even drive me off, let alone kill me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I waved my hand to dispel my magnifier and made my decision. I kept making it with every step I took down the far side of the hill. My stomach was roiling because probably most of my choice was motivated by valuing these people's lives less than my own comfort.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A wave of need washed through me. I wish I could say it was for my wife's embrace, but really what I wanted was Mistress's hand on my head, telling me that I was good, telling me that it was all her fault and that I didn't need to feel guilty.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;From the back of the hill, I hiked a mile cross-country through woodland to the main road. I'd been planning to just sprint the rest of the way, but by that point it was full dark and probably I would hit a tree, so I took my time. The trip took me about two hours in all. I can't imagine what someone would have thought if they'd come across me on the road, strolling along in the nearly pitch-black, humming The Black Parade to myself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The guards must have heard the crunch of my boots on the dirt before they saw me, because one raised her lantern and shouted, "Who goes there!? Show yourself!"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My pulse started racing, my tail lashed, and my guts twisted as adrenaline hit me. Planning time was over. Acting time was go.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I obliged by casting a light spell, which illuminated me in eerie red. I don't know if that was truly necessary, given the horns that curved from my forehead and my previously mentioned lashing tail. There was only one kind of creature with that combination of appendages, and until the last handful of years it had been relegated to myth and ancient history. I wasn't just aura farming for the fun of it, I was trying to keep them safe by scaring them off.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Stop where you are!" the guard with the lantern shouted.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kill anyone who draws against you or otherwise stands in your way.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I didn't. "Drop your weapons, run away, and I won't kill you," I shouted back. Hopefully they were smart enough to put two and two together and figure out that meant if they &lt;em&gt;drew&lt;/em&gt; their weapons that I &lt;em&gt;would&lt;/em&gt; kill them.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Sound the alarm," ordered the guard who hadn't shouted. He lowered his spear to point at me. The other dropped her weapon and grabbed for the bell-rope. Hey, that's a good idea, maybe I could keep them from sounding the alarm. I grabbed a knife from my bandolier and flung it. It missed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;CLANG! CLANG! CLANG! CLANG!&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;For a moment, I imagined how cool it would have been if that had cut the rope in half. Unfortunately, I didn't get accuracy along with my speed and strength.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The female guard still hadn't pointed a weapon at me. I had to kill the male guard one way or the other now, but maybe I could do it in a way that made it clear that she couldn't beat me? I flashstepped forward, closing the distance like a bullet, and reappeared with my sword impaling him, stabbed straight through his armor and also his lung. I'd intended to get his heart so that he'd suffer less.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sorry, dude.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He gasped. Blood drooled out of his mouth.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"D-demon!" the remaining guard screamed as she fled toward the fortress. Right idea, wrong direction. I yanked the sword out of the man I'd killed, but even with super strength it was kind of stuck on the breastplate and bones and stuff, and it made a horrible grinding noise. I flinched as his blood spattered against my face and tossed him off the bridge and into the moat.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The other guard was running like I wanted, but not to get away; she was trying to warn the fort about the nature of the threat. A bell couldn't communicate that a &lt;em&gt;demon&lt;/em&gt; was attacking. I ran past her, then put myself between her and the fort.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Run away," I growled. "Flee for your life." Please, get the hint. I could've killed you &lt;em&gt;easy&lt;/em&gt;, and the only reason I didn't is because you haven't—&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She drew her sword and looked at me with idiot bravery shining through her fear. For &lt;em&gt;fuck's&lt;/em&gt; sake.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Frustration got the better of me and the woman didn't get a clean death. Sorry, lady. I hope they bury you and don't just toss you all in a bonfire. I forced myself to look at her while I whipped out a knife and added two notches to the edge of my sword.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The sound of a chain clanking drew my attention just in time to see the gatehouse's portcullis falling shut. Too late.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Too late for them, that is. I had multiple seconds to dash underneath it and into the gatehouse before it closed, which was plenty of time. It was a plain, narrow room lit by torches in the corners. There was a lot of yelling around me — four guards were surrounding me, but they hadn't gotten their swords out yet because my speed had surprised them — but as soon as I appeared inside, the &lt;em&gt;second &lt;/em&gt;portcullis started to drop; the one that would seal the gatehouse from the bailey. I had even more time to duck under it than I had the first, though, so I did.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Then I was attacked by five soldiers, one of whom managed to give me a minor cut on my arm. Dispatching them took a couple minutes. The four in the gatehouse were cut off from me for now and weren't so brain-dead as to pull a sword on me when we couldn't even touch each other, so I was able to ignore them for the moment. Someone would let them out once I was out of sight, probably.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Like that, I carved a bloody trail into the fortress, occasionally pausing to notch my sword. After the first deaths, I grew colder to the killing. Never completely numb, but not losing my temper like I had with the suicidally heroic second guard. I would cry later, in private, as I reviewed my notches. I kept track because I needed to know, needed to know the size of the stain I was bearing. I tried, once, to completely disconnect, to tell myself that I was simply a doll without will and therefore could not be blamed, but the guilt and shame hit me even harder when I stopped dissociating.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Whenever I could, I repeated my offer, though I don't think I managed as good a delivery as I had the first time. A few took me up on it. Most didn't. The worst part was the man who drew his sword, took a swing against me, and then fled. My orders were such that I needed to chase him down, which caused another fight and more deaths.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It really wasn't the least bit fair. Someone from the real world outmatched anyone from here a dozen times over, no matter our actual physical ability. I was Mistress's tactical warhead, and she deployed me with absolute precision. I wasn't absolutely invincible — I sustained a few wounds in the process — but nothing that I even needed to stop and magically heal.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I'm sure it terrified people,&lt;/em&gt; Mistress once told me, &lt;em&gt;the thought of someone like you roaming around with free will! Hence this delightful device was invented.&lt;/em&gt; She'd hooked a finger under my collar and used it to yank my head back and forth while I whined.&lt;em&gt; And even &lt;/em&gt;then&lt;em&gt; it was decided that your kind were too dangerous, and the knowledge of your summoning and control was sealed away!&lt;/em&gt; Sealed away until she'd unearthed it and used what she'd found to rip me from my home and set me to work.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It took me longer than it should have to find the dungeons, because I was looking for a downward staircase, but of course if there had been a basement here it would be underwater. The dungeon was on the ground floor, in the back of the keep, close to the barracks. The wooden door splintered under my boot and I rushed inside, hoping to take anyone there by surprise. I was rewarded by a dumbfounded expression on the warden's face. By the look of him, there was a reason why he was &lt;em&gt;here&lt;/em&gt; and not with a sword in his hand defending the place. In an instant, my blade was pressed to his throat.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Drop your weapons. Run away. And you'll live," I told him, quietly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Okay." He held up his empty hands and nodded as vehemently as he could with a sword under his chin. "Okay."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Wait," I added. "Do you have a key for the cells?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Pocket," he said, reaching down for his pocket. I nodded. He stepped close to hand it to me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No, he stepped close to stab me in the kidney. I hadn't been paying close enough attention. Not a key, a knife. I gasped in pain. His eyes went wide and triumphant and he stabbed me again, but he didn't get to hear the noise I made because my sword went through his neck.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Stupid," I muttered, though I wasn't sure if I was cursing myself or him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I was leaking all over my clothes. Also, let me be clear, it hurt very badly. I'm tough as hell (literally) but that doesn't mean I don't feel pain. That wound probably would have killed a normal person, but for me it would heal eventually. I actually wasn't sure how long something like this would take because I always just used magic. I cast heal and shut the wounds, then notched my sword. Poor bastard really thought he'd gotten me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As I knelt down to rifle through the warden's pockets, the prisoners clustered up to the bars, murmuring, but when they saw my horns and tail they all shied back into the shadows.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Free the prisoners and escort them out of the fortress. Typical bodyguard priorities&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;(which meant that I should protect them from all harm, even if it meant harming myself, but I should let them die rather than let myself be killed)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hero time. As though I knew anything about that. Took a few deep breaths and forced some emotion back into my voice. I wasn't sure if I was putting on a mask or taking one off, but I needed to be something other than a reluctant killing machine for the moment.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Relax," I announced. "I'm here to free you." My search didn't turn up any keys, and a glance around the room didn't reveal any, either. Maybe it was hidden or maybe I'd just failed to find it because the room was only lit by a flickering oil lamp, but it didn't matter that much. I notched my sword for the warden, then used his tunic to clean off the blood and sheathed it. This wasn't a high-security magical prison, so I didn't really even &lt;em&gt;need&lt;/em&gt; a key. I walked right up to the rusty bars and grabbed hold.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"All of us?" came a suspicious, masculine voice from inside.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I looked up and squinted, but there wasn't enough light to see clearly. Five or six people in the cell, I thought. "All of you."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A young man stepped forward a little, enough that I could see his wide, uncomprehending eyes. "Why?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I don't believe in carceral justice. I'm a bleeding heart liberal." I suppose I'm glad that all the shit I've done hasn't ruined my dumbass sense of humor. It helped that, as a chick with red skin, horns, and a tail, people kind of &lt;em&gt;expected&lt;/em&gt; me to say shit that they didn't understand. Mistress thought it was cute. I shifted my grip, then strained. It hurt, but it worked, and the bars slowly bent like clay. "Don't all rush out at once." I moved on to the next cell, which only had one person.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Wait, don't, that's—" The boy's cry was cut off as the first speaker put a hand over his mouth.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"What he means to say, ma'am, is the one in that cell is a murderer. Killed five so far." I looked at him and his eyes darted to his feet, then he haltingly bowed his head. "Begging your pardon. It's your grace's choice, of course."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Don't," I said, cringing. "Don't call me that. I'm not nobility, I'm just a—" &lt;em&gt;A blue-collar Jane&lt;/em&gt; was the joke I wanted to make (although my collar was actually silver) but that's not what I said. "—slave." It felt gross to say that. But I couldn't help it, because it felt good, too. Right. A relief. A conditioned reaction, of course. That's how Mistress defined our relationship. "And I'm rescuing &lt;em&gt;everyone&lt;/em&gt;, regardless of &lt;em&gt;why&lt;/em&gt; they're here."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Hot tip," I continued as I stepped back to start on the next set of bars, yammering automatically to try and shake off the fuzzy feelings that built up in my skull when I called myself that. "If you ever have the misfortune to encounter another demon, the traditional mode of address is Hellboy. Or Hellgirl, for a demoness."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"And that will … &lt;em&gt;please&lt;/em&gt; them, … Hellgirl?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"They might think it's funny, yeah." If they have decent taste in comics, at least. Another heave and the bars were plenty wide for the woman in the cell. "If what he said is true," I addressed her as I wiped sweat off my forehead, "I want to warn you. Don't point a weapon at me or I'll kill you. Or at any of them." I tilted my head at the first cell.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Wouldn't dream of it," she said, evenly. She was plain-looking, with dirty red hair and the same prison garb as the rest of them, but she held herself with far more poise. She also had a pair of fox-like ears on the top of her head, with fur that matched her hair. Beastkin, probably from Daumeir if I had to guess. No wonder she was in a separate cell. I could tell by her face that she was trying to parse my accent and figure out where I was from. Fortunately, even speaking a language that had been magically delivered into my brain, my accent was firmly American and thus uniquely bizarre to the people from this world.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I wondered whether it was true about the murders, and what the circumstances were. A female murderer, especially from a minority group, was more likely to have killed to protect herself in my experience. Maybe I was biased. It was easy to imagine that she'd been assaulted, killed the rapist, was imprisoned, and had her crime exaggerated to the other prisoners. I decided to believe that, because it made me feel better about letting her out. Yippee, I'm one of the good guys!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"That goes for the rest of you, too. Don't get any ideas about shanking each other. Play nice and let me rescue you. Magic, too, obviously," I added for the benefit of the fox-girl. Not all beastkin were proficient with magic, but the ones who were outclassed human mages significantly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Shank?" mumbled a woman's voice, and someone else shushed her.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I walked back to the broken door. "Alright, new friends. Time to play duckling, now." They hobbled out of the cells and clustered behind me. One of them, slower than the rest, had a blindfold on and was being led by an older woman. "I'm guessing the blindfold isn't just fashionable?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"N-no, Hellgirl," the woman said, and I fought down a smirk at the name. Stupid. I can't believe I said that. "He's blind."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I sighed. "Alright. Here, I'll lead him." I took his hand from her, then noticed that there was still someone else in the cell. I sighed again. "Come on," I said, starting to be annoyed. "Let's go."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Please, no, ma'am," the prisoner stammered. "I'll just get recaptured and punished."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Entirely plausible, but it didn't change anything. "Don't care," I said, "come &lt;em&gt;on&lt;/em&gt;."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She curled into a ball and shook her head. "For the love of &lt;em&gt;fucking&lt;/em&gt;," I groaned, then squeezed through the bars and into the cell. She started shaking as I got closer.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kill anyone who draws against you or otherwise stands in your way.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Was this standing in my way? Did I need to kill her? I touched the hilt of my sword, unhappy about the prospect. No; no, she was &lt;em&gt;impeding&lt;/em&gt; me certainly, by not following instructions, but I wouldn't say she was &lt;em&gt;standing in my way&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I'm not going to hurt you," I said, feeling relieved about the fact. "I'm just gonna—" I bent down, put my left arm around her waist, and hefted her over my shoulder into a fireman carry. She squeaked in alarm, but was smart enough not to struggle.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Maybe next time Mistress had me do this sort of rescue I'd suggest an exception. Like: &lt;em&gt;if any of the prisoners want to stay, you can let them&lt;/em&gt;. I spent a lot of time fantasizing how I could change my orders to make them more efficient, but she usually rejected my ideas. She thought it was amusing when my tasks were complicated by logic errors. There was some kind of sick irony that a programmer had been made into something like a living algorithm.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Left hand for the reluctant prisoner, right hand for my sword… "Here." I wrapped my tail around the blind guy's wrist. "Hold onto my tail, I guess. No yanking."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yes, Hellgirl," he said, squeezing it slightly, his forehead wrinkling. It probably felt kind of weird to him, sort of like a friendly snake covered in skin. Having a stranger squeeze my tail felt kind of weird to &lt;em&gt;me&lt;/em&gt;, but I would have to cope. It was &lt;em&gt;definitely&lt;/em&gt; going to get yanked at some point in the next hour and I needed to prepare myself psychologically for that fact.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Automatically, I reviewed my list of orders. It took me a couple minutes, and when I finished, a shiver of pleasure thrilled through me. Good. I was a good girl. Another conditioned reaction.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Back in the real world, my memory hadn't been all that great. That was the first thing that Mistress worked on, because if I &lt;em&gt;forgot&lt;/em&gt; an order, I could disobey it. The magic of the collar &lt;em&gt;enforced&lt;/em&gt; commands, but it relied on my own mind to recognize and interpret what those commands were. Before you ask, no, I can't do the trick of conveniently forgetting things that I don't like. That's one of my top five standing orders, so if I— I'm getting off track. The specifics of my orders and how the collar works aren't something I need to get into right now. Maybe next chapter.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My entourage and I left the dungeon and I led them through the fortress. I tried to take a different route than the one that I'd come in with, to spare them the sight of the mess I'd made, but we still came across a few. They gasped and murmured among themselves, but I was splattered with blood all over so I'm not sure what they were expecting.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was smooth sailing. I began to happily imagine that the surviving soldiers had realized that they had no hope of defeating me and also that I had no interest in going out of my way to kill anyone. I was just here to release the prisoners, not to assassinate whatever petty lord held court here. It would have been so nice if I could have just shown up, had a chat with whoever lived here, and worked out a way to accomplish my task without death, but nobody ever wanted to dicker with a demon. We had a reputation for being tricky and legalistic.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Gosh, I wonder why.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Then, when we were almost back to the main hall, the one where the lord of the fortress would have met with petitioners, we ran into a trap.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There was a line of salt barring the doorway.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You may not pass above a line of salt. You may not disrupt such a line either, obviously.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I blinked at it, mouth going dry. How could they know about that? If they knew that, then they might know the other ways I was restricted, and if they knew that, then—&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No, no, they didn't know anything. It was for the same reason Mistress had given me that rule: because she thought it was funny. It was myth, and it amused her to sometimes force me to act in ways that corresponded with mythical depictions of demons. In this case, it was a convenient way for her to easily fuck with me, restrict my access to parts of my home, and make sure I didn't move her bookmark in anything she was reading.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;At other points in time she'd prevented me from magically healing wounds caused by silver weapons, required that I act afraid of fire, and forced me to count any small objects spilled in front of me. I said, &lt;em&gt;no, that's werewolves, frankensteins, and vampires&lt;/em&gt; but she just laughed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Staring at it, I tried to plot a route around it. If we backtracked … No, there would be a reason this was here. They didn't want me to take this route. There would be some other trap elsewhere, or maybe that way would be sealed by salt, too.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I turned to the prisoners and met the eyes of the fox-girl because she was the only one who didn't flinch at my gaze. I opened my mouth.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You may not ask someone else to help you circumvent a rule. This includes gestures, vague implications, significant glances, etc.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I closed my mouth and looked back at the salt.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I probably could cross it, though my mind shied away from the thought. My collar couldn't actually control my mind or my body.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No. No, I couldn't. I trembled, ashamed at my eagerness to justify disobedience. I was a good girl.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This isn't what Mistress meant, though. If she'd thought that someone would have done this, then she would've removed the order. It was a mistake.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Or was it? It wasn't my place to question my orders. Perhaps Mistress had leaked this weakness as a way to test me. Or maybe it would better serve her for me to be seen to have these weaknesses, to convince her enemies that I could be easily diverted only to remove the weakness later.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;If I took a running leap … momentum would carry me over. I'd need to somehow convince myself that I was running and jumping for some &lt;em&gt;other&lt;/em&gt; reason or else my collar would block it. Even if I successfully got over, my collar would automatically register that I had broken a rule and would punish me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I shouldn't. Mistress wouldn't want that. I sighed as, after five rounds of back-and-forth in my head, I realized the truth. It was relaxing. It felt good to give in. For this mission, at least, Mistress didn't want me to be an infallible tactical warhead. She wanted me to be a creature of myth with weaknesses that could be exploited. She wanted me to have the potential for failure. If I circumvented those rules, her plans would be ruined, and I would be a very bad girl.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I would need to think of another way out. I nodded to myself, then turned. "This route won't work," I announced. "We'll go out a window."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Why?" piped up the murderer.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;You may not ask someone else to help you circumvent a rule. This includes gestures, vague implications, significant glances, etc.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The question put me in an awkward position. Telling her that I couldn't cross the salt was as good as asking her to help me circumvent it; to satisfy my own sense of Mistress's desires I had to make my best attempt to deflect. But my mind was free enough that I could still hope she was smart enough to see through it. "There's a trap ahead," I lied. "I can't risk your safety." I can tell because of the pixels and from having seen many traps in my time. These fucking memes were going to haunt me until the day I died.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No, wait, I've got a worse one. Of course there's a trap ahead, I'm standing right in front of her! Not that I had a dick right then, but, you know. Kind of a philosophical question: if a trans girl doesn't have a dick, is she a trap?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She narrowed her eyes at me, but I ignored her and started for the door we'd come in through. Everyone else, at least, was happy to do whatever I told them.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I was back through the door when she called out, "Is it this? This line of salt?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I twitched. "It's not the salt," I said. "That's stupid."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I brushed it aside for you," she said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I turned to look.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The line was still there, and she was smirking at me. "It &lt;em&gt;is&lt;/em&gt;."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I set my jaw and didn't answer.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"You're &lt;em&gt;embarrassed&lt;/em&gt;." Her grin broadened. "The demon is &lt;em&gt;ashamed&lt;/em&gt; that she can't cross a line of salt!"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Laugh at me," I growled. "See what happens."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Nothing would happen. I wasn't allowed to harm the prisoners.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The expressions on the other prisoner's faces indicated that they very much did not want to see what would happen, but the vulpine murderess didn't seem worried at all. She licked her lips quickly and looked me up and down, a smile still dancing around her lips. Her tail wagged gently.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She was fucking &lt;em&gt;bratting&lt;/em&gt; at me. Very suddenly, images flashed through my mind of treating her &lt;em&gt;exactly&lt;/em&gt; how she was asking to be. Maybe I could even do it without &lt;em&gt;harming&lt;/em&gt; her.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hey, Mistress hadn't totally ground out all my dominant impulses!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My face must have revealed something of my thoughts, because she quickly turned away and scattered the salt with her foot. "There," she said. "We can go this way now."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I huffed in frustration and marched through the now-clear doorway. Almost out. The main hall would have been a good place for an ambush, a nice wide area that could let them take advantage of numbers, but maybe they didn't have that many numbers anymore? Also, if they were planning an ambush here, they wouldn't've left the salt line. As we crossed through the hall, I noted that the other doors were blocked by lines of salt as well, so we were probably home free.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Nothing stopped us as we exited the keep and crossed the bailey. No visible lanterns or torches along the top of the outer wall, either, though any guards up there had probably extinguished them for stealth.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The guards that had been stuck in the gatehouse weren't there anymore, so either they went out the front or somebody had let them into the bailey. Both portcullises were closed, though, so I sheathed my sword and set to cranking it open one-handed. I had to do it at something approximating normal speed — the mechanism would jam if I cranked it too fast — so it took several minutes. Then I led everyone through and started cranking open the outer portcullis.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That's what I was going to do, at least, but I was taken by surprise when as soon as I stepped through, the portcullis dropped again, released from a mechanism higher up in the gatehouse.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hindered by my burden, I instinctively tried to leap forward. Except the blind guy was holding tight to my tail, and he couldn't help but yank on it as it tore from his grasp.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I made an embarrassing noise. The blind man stumbled forward, into the path of the falling portcullis.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Free the prisoners and escort them out of the fortress. Typical bodyguard priorities.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The memory of Mistress's voice echoed in my head, but I was stuck because leaping back to knock him out of the way might harm the woman I was carrying. Head still spinning from having my tail pulled so roughly, I hesitated a moment too long, then sprang at him and bounced off the portcullis as it slammed in my face.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Fuck!" I yowled.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Through the stars flashing in my vision, I could see that the fox-girl had grabbed the man's shoulder and pulled him back, so that was good. She was proving herself to be more useful than I'd expected.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There was another noise above me, and now I was trapped in the gatehouse with one of the prisoners. My strength and speed wouldn't do much to let me immediately escape; I couldn't bend a portcullis like I had the bars in the dungeon. I might be able to lift one, though, but I probably wouldn't have enough time, because…&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Remember at the start of all this how I was thinking that I might end up getting boiling oil dumped on me?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I dropped my burden onto the stone floor, where she looked up at me with confused and fearful eyes. My face probably looked pretty wild. I didn't think this would kill me, probably, but it was sure going to hurt.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Curl into a ball," I ordered. "Make yourself as small as possible."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She was cooperative about &lt;em&gt;this&lt;/em&gt;, at least. With her shivering and clutching her ankles, I covered her as completely as I could with my body, then, as a last minute thought, stuffed one of my leather gloves between my teeth and bit down.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I felt heat radiating down from above, but it didn't hurt nearly as much as I thought. In fact, it felt kind of nice compared to the chill of the air. Had Mistress put some kind of protection spell on me without telling me? Surprised, I twisted and looked up.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;About six feet above me was a translucent magical barrier that was catching the boiling oil. Heat was radiating from the levitating pool. Dumbfounded, I looked back to the bailey to see the beastkin murderess with her arms outstretched and an expression of intense focus on her face.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Significantly&lt;/em&gt; more useful than I'd expected. I patted the cowering woman on the face and, glove still clutched in my teeth, dashed to the inner portcullis, grabbed the bottom, and strained myself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This was way harder than bending the bars, but still, it probably weighed less than a car. Not that I'd actually been able to test out lifting a car, so I guess the comparison is pretty meaningless. My retinue acted quickly, ducking under as soon as there was enough room. Fox-girl was the last one, moving slowly and carefully to avoid ruining her concentration.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I dropped the inner portcullis with a crash and raced to the outer gate. We were now in a &lt;em&gt;very&lt;/em&gt; dangerous situation — if that barrier dropped it would be total failure — so I heaved it up without wasting time listening to the complaints of my bones and muscles. Everyone passed through, even the reticent woman, and then I followed. As soon as I was clear, the spell dropped, dumping all the oil onto the ground at once. I sprang backward, narrowly dodging the splash.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Home stretch. This time I scooped up the blind guy and encouraged the rest of them to run with a wide sweeping gesture and drew my sword again. They all went eagerly, and I took up the rear, hopping backwards. Like I'd thought, the guards sent arrows after us, which I was able to swat out of the air before they could hit any of my ducklings. That felt cool and fun to do until I missed one and the arrow hit me in the leg.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Once we had sufficient distance, I set the blind man back down next to the woman who had originally been leading him, ripped out the arrow, and healed it with magic. Finally, I spat the glove out of my mouth and pulled it back on my hand. There were tooth-holes in it. Probably if I'd actually gotten deep-fried I would have ripped it to shreds.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A little belatedly, I realized that we were all standing around in the dark and they probably were less used to it than I was, so I cast a light for them. The prisoners were looking at me expectantly, but something was nagging at the back of my mind. Had I forgotten something?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Quickly, I mentally went over all of my orders.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kill anyone who draws against you or otherwise stands in your way.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Ah, fuck, the archers. They'd drawn against me, so I needed to deal with them. Boiling oil … eh, that wasn't a weapon that you draw or anything that stood in my way.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;So I got to climb up the wall like I had originally thought about, and ended up notching my sword three more times.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;From the wall, I could see that the prisoners were still standing around. Probably they wouldn't be able to just head out into the darkness, so I gathered a couple of the torches from the people I'd killed, brought them down, and handed them around.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Now what?" asked the older man. Several of the prisoners were shivering. It wasn't very warm out tonight.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"You're free!" I said, grinning and spreading my hands like I was announcing that they'd won a new car. "Go nuts!"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Hellgirl, um. Respectfully…" the old woman paused, the one holding the blind man's hand, probably trying to figure out how to ask what she wanted while remaining polite. "Where should we … go?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"No idea," I said. "This is as far as I can take you, and now I must return from whence I have come." I was already looking forward to getting back home, though it was going to be a long run cross-country to get there. Maybe I could lay my head in Mistress's lap and she'd pet my hair.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The prisoners didn't like that answer very much, but they muttered among themselves and, after a few minutes, a group of them set off down the road while another ducked into the underbrush of the forest.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Except one. The beastkin woman had been left out of the conference and followed no one. She hadn't taken a torch, either. Instead, she was looking up at the sky, deep in thought. I studied her, a little curious, until finally she nodded to herself, cast a light spell, and moved to go into the trees in a different direction from the others.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Before you take off," I said, because I &lt;em&gt;had&lt;/em&gt; to know. "Before you &lt;em&gt;leave&lt;/em&gt;, I mean, can I ask you a question?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She turned back toward me and gave me half of a smile. "You just saved my life. Yes, one question should clear our debt."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"You've got magic. Those cells weren't enchanted or anything. You could've broken out whenever you wanted. Why didn't you?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I have a hard time imagining how a magical barrier or a light could have helped me escape."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Presumably you can cast other spells."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She laughed quietly. "With my charges, I was almost certainly going to be executed. But if I used my magic to escape … I probably would have been caught and killed right then and there." She shrugged. "I suppose I just wanted to live as long as possible."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I'm glad you did," I said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"So I &lt;em&gt;am&lt;/em&gt; the one you were here to rescue?" Her eyes brightened and her tail wagged slightly. "Who sent you?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I laughed. "No," I said, answering neither question. "I just prefer it when people survive, is all."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"A surprising sentiment, given—"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Given the fact that I'd directly murdered nineteen people tonight, I didn't want to hear her say. "Not my choice," I said, sharply.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She started to respond, but suddenly I badly needed the conversation to be over. I ended it by quickly turning and sprinting out of sight fast enough that I would seem to have vanished. Demons usually get the last word when we want to.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I clenched my fists. Stupid bitch, getting on my case for stuff I couldn't control. She should be grateful that Mistress had arbitrarily ordered me to rescue the prisoners instead of killing them. She should be thanking her beastkin gods that coin had come up heads rather than tails. Mistress was fickle, and I was sure that the fate of the prisoners had just been a way to screw with me and amuse herself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I&lt;/em&gt; should thank her, I realized. I should thank her for allowing me to do something that felt heroic instead of slaughtering innocents. I shivered. I should get on the ground and kiss her feet and do whatever I needed to do so that she would let me rescue more people later. Even if those people weren't perfectly grateful.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A wave of needy submissiveness washed over me. Knowing that this attitude had been conditioned, that I had been warped by torture and magic and training into someone who thought these kinds of things, into someone who could remember a list of 30 orders and follow them perfectly, into someone whose submissive streak had been contorted into something that controlled her life, didn't help me resist.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I could be grateful &lt;em&gt;for&lt;/em&gt; them. I &lt;em&gt;would&lt;/em&gt; be grateful for them, grateful for Mistress's mercy. I would be good. Good. Good girl.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;With thoughts of submitting for Mistress spinning in my head, I departed for home.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
