      <pubDate>Mon, 26 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Jay is a meticulous barista, living his life with discipline and care: he will not be like other men; he will be better than them. But his coworker and roommate Herb renders this goal near impossible by being an all-around nuisance. Doesn't help that he's also hot...&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But everything changes when they stumble upon a pair of very special shark plushies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I Hugged a Blåhaj Too Tight and Turned Into a Sharkgirl is a 20k words self-indulgent, horny, and comedic romance between two trans girls with very different takes on life, work, and identity.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2120427-i-hugged-a-blhaj-too-tight-and-turned-into-a-sharkgirl/chapter/2120431/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter One: The Reward of a Job Well Done&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;div class="wi_news"&gt; &lt;div class="wi_news_title"&gt;&lt;i class="fa fa-exclamation-triangle" aria-hidden="true" style="padding-right:5px;"&gt;&lt;/i&gt; Announcement&lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="wi_news_body"&gt;Hello hello hello! Sorry for the big hiatus on here. 2025 wasn’t a great year for me writing-wise, but I did complete one story, this one! It was a really fun project to work on, and I hope you’ll have as much fun reading it as I had writing it :) The whole story &lt;em&gt;(including an exclusive 2,5k words smut scene)&lt;/em&gt; is available now on my &lt;a href="https://www.patreon.com/collection/1472846?view=expanded" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"&gt;patreon&lt;/a&gt;, where you’ll also be able to read the first chapter of my upcoming vampire story as soon as I finish it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And quick reminder that my transbian minecraft youtuber silly romance Face Reveal is available as an epub on itch: &lt;a href="https://aquerelle.itch.io/face-reveal" rel="nofollow" target="_blank"&gt;https://aquerelle.itch.io/face-reveal&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="sp-wrap sp-wrap-default"&gt; &lt;div class="sp-head" title="Expand"&gt; Whole Story Content Warnings &lt;/div&gt; &lt;div class="sp-body folded"&gt; &lt;p&gt;Internalised transphobia, misogyny, sex (fade to black) and mentions of sex&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div class="spdiv"&gt;[collapse]&lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;/div&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What’s weird is that Willow asked us not to &lt;i&gt;hug&lt;/i&gt; the new blåhaj,” Jay says. “And, like, what kind of warning is that—”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Tut-tut-tut.” Herb cuts him off, leans back on the marble counter, right in between the cash-till and the grinder, and shakes his stupid blonde head in disapproval, avoiding Jay’s eyes. “I’ll stop you right there, buddy. It is not blew-hi, but &lt;i&gt;blow&lt;/i&gt;-hi. Repeat after me. Blooow-hi.” He pinches the air, lifting his hand at the ‘blå’ and dropping it at the ‘haj’.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Herb is Jay’s coworker. He’s a hottie, a nerd, and a pain in the ass.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Blew-hi,” Jay indulges him. It’s not like any of them speak Swedish anyway.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Herb chuckles and waggles his index. “Mm, that’s not it. Blow. Like a… Like blow! You say blew, I say &lt;i&gt;blooow.&lt;/i&gt; Hear that little difference?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No, Jay doesn’t really hear that little difference. It sounds exactly the same to his ear. Okay, maybe not the &lt;i&gt;same &lt;/i&gt;same, but he pronounced the ‘u’ almost like an ‘o’ and Herb pronounced the ‘o’ almost like an ‘u’ and for the last time, they don’t speak Swedish, aren’t planning on learning it, and they don’t even serve meatballs; it’s the fucking chic little café of a private swimming pool, not IKEA. So what gives? Who cares? Jay just wanted to warn him about Willow’s plushie policy, not fight about &lt;i&gt;linguistics.&lt;/i&gt; Herb’s starting to piss him off with a useless debate — again — and wasting valuable work time — &lt;i&gt;again. &lt;/i&gt;One day, that boy is going to get them fired, and then they won’t be able to pay their rent any more.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Because yes, Herb is Jay’s coworker, but he’s also, regretfully, his roommate.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Blew,” Jay says, making a constructive attempt not to groan.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Keep it professional. There are customers. There are tasks to attend to.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Herb’s eyes flicker up to meet Jay’s for a second. Deep, mesmerising, brown eyes, long lashes — all of which, for the record, are outright wasted on a &lt;i&gt;boy, &lt;/i&gt;especially one named &lt;i&gt;Herb&lt;/i&gt; — and a scowl that makes Jay’s heart skip a beat.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Blow!” Herb says, slamming his hand flat on the counter and raising his voice just high enough for the closest table to pick up on it and stare at the two waiters. Damn it, if he continues being this obnoxious, he really is going to get them fired, and he’s going to get them fired &lt;i&gt;today&lt;/i&gt; with a tortious interference suit to boot. “Uu. Oh. Uu. Oh. See? Just relax your tongue a little. It’s not that hard!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, whatever. Blow, blue, bleh. &lt;i&gt;Blah, blah, blah.”&lt;/i&gt; Jay looks over Herb’s shoulder and shouts, “Excuse him! He’s been feeling rather stressed out lately.” Then he approaches Herb, whispers, “You’re making a scene,” and pulls the pretty boy by the arm, almost closing the gap between them, learning in the process that, today, Herb smells like pine and wood chips. “And keep your hands off the counter. I just got it cleaned.” To prove his point, he produces a wet washcloth from his apron’s front pocket and wipes the counter once more, never breaking eye contact. Giving him the stink eye. Letting him know the measure of his annoyance.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Herb snorts and slaps his hand on Jay’s back. “Aww, look at you. Isn’t it adorable when you’re scared to admit defeat? Ooh, yes it is. Yes it is.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Great, now he’s talking to Jay not only like a dog, which is humiliating enough, but &lt;i&gt;his&lt;/i&gt; dog, which is way, way worse. Bringing back gross memories of getting stuck in the trenches of the school social ladder. Memories he prefers stay firmly locked in the High School Experience part of his mind, next to all-time classics like witnessing the ways boys behave behind their locker room’s doors when adults and girls are gone, or being the sidekick of a sidekick of an almost but not quite popular guy for two consecutive years. The days of being people’s pet are long gone. He swats Herb’s hand away.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“By the way,” Herb continues unperturbed, “aren’t you supposed to take the orders? I’m the one on bar duty today.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jay sighs. “Then let’s swap.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Bad idea.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sorry to break the news, but you, my guy, have no sense of hygiene.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No sense of— You’re the cuter one! We get more tips when you take orders.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The cuter one. As if. Jay rolls his eyes and continues wiping.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Waiter!” someone suddenly shouts, rattling a spoon on his empty glass. Both Jay and Herb turn to look at him. It’s their worst customer, a graying man, dressed to the nines, who always sits at the furthest spot from the bar, in order to be able to see all customers and waiters in front of him and still be able to check on the saltwater pool he’s so proud of to his left. It’s the manager. He’s leaning on the large glass window that spans from one end of the café to the other for at least eighteen metres of uninterrupted glass — one of the largest in the world, he would point out — and he looks positively annoyed. It’s the manager, and it’s &lt;i&gt;urgent.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The waiters look at each other intensely, but Jay refuses to move; he even takes a step back towards the sink, smirking. He’s already won this one. His hands are all wet, and Herb is closer to the bar’s exit. There’s only one solution that is both timely and doesn’t involve getting dangerously close to each other again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Fine,” Herb eventually says, almost growls, “but next time you do the dishes, I will tie you up, and I’m not even kidding!” Then he takes an empty plate and marches up to the glass window, not wasting a second. He’s just fast enough to show that his priority is the customer’s satisfaction, but stays steady and professional and avoids making his steps echo down the hall. He’s &lt;i&gt;good.&lt;/i&gt; One more reason for him to take orders. He’s got a way better swagger than Jay’s bulky and awkward trot.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Way better ass, too, but that’s beside the point.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jay starts pouring water on the dishes, deciding then and there that he’s done with Herb for the day, and that he wouldn’t warn him about Willow’s new blåhaj. Wouldn’t even mention it again. His loss. If there was something fishy going on with their other roommate’s shark plush, Herb will discover it the hard way.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;&lt;b&gt;˙ 𓆝 𓆟 𓆞 𓆝 𓆟 .&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It’s late, and he’s back at home, at the sink again. Herb is taking his daily hour-long shower, and Willow is asleep; she’s probably been asleep since before they came back. It’s &lt;i&gt;really&lt;/i&gt; late. But there were dirty plates, forks, and spoons, and Jay hates waking up to a crowded sink.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He’s always preferred staying behind the bar. He’s good at grinder dialling, puck prep, milk frothing and latte art, and he knows how to properly clean. The more dirty glasses pile up in the kitchen, the more he feels like it’s his duty to clean them all, and the more he cleans them, the more he’s at peace; it’s meditative. It’s like he’s making amends for his sins. He might be an uptight stickler, but at least he’s not like those guys who mull around doing nothing, or worse, those who pretend they’re some kind of feminist because they do the bare minimum. No, Jay is a serious man: be that at home or at the café, he does the job, he does it well, and he doesn’t ask anything in return. The reward of a job well done is plenty enough. And what’s more, Herb always leaves specks and smudges, which is not up to par for a café like the one they work at. Not up to par at all, really.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That’s why Jay loves taking care of the dishes at home, too. That, and cooking, and vacuuming, and all-around cleaning the place. His tolerance for filth is way lower than Herb’s, and he would never &lt;i&gt;ever&lt;/i&gt; let Willow clean. As a woman, she already has too much nonsense to deal with, so making her feel as if she has to take care of the chores is the last thing Jay wants. He’s even terrified of the idea, if he’s entirely honest. He’d hate to be like Herb: a dirty, macho deadbeat who doesn’t even know how to wash his own clothes. The prime example of everything wrong with men, despite not exactly looking the part, what with his long hair and perfectly shaven face.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Thus, at the café, he cleans. And at home, he cleans. And he likes it. It gives him purpose and offers him a way out when life is too much.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Granted he doesn’t stare into a spoon for half an hour.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Yes, the handle is rather pretty; its curves flow and twist like petals and thorns. It reminds him of his mother, who collected beautiful souvenir spoons from all over the world, and it makes him wonder again if he doesn’t want to do the same as her one day. Yes, also, the bowl of the spoon is old and rugged, busy with indents and budding rust. He briefly tries to remember where and when he acquired it, what the story behind it is, and if it isn’t time to replace it. But those observations only accounted for a minute, give or take, of his fascination for the spoon.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No, the twenty-nine others are spent on his face, reflected in the back of the spoon. Distorted. Crude. Obscenely crude.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He brings it close, so close, until he is reduced to a blurry brown. And the world fades out for a while; he gets a little sense of peace. Then, methodically, he slides it further and further away from his eyes, and slowly, his features appear. His nose, sweaty and hairy. His brow, thick and dishevelled. And his jaw, square and uneven. The whole thing looks unfamiliar. Uncanny. What is all of that? It’s human, it’s a man, it’s him, presumably, but he has trouble believing it. And he’s engrossed with the feeling it gives him; it’s like repeating a word over and over until it loses all meaning and sounds alien. His face looks alien. That’s fun — right? He shivers. Then he brings the spoon closer again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What are you doing?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The spoon slips out of his grip and falls in the sink with a clang as Jay turns towards the hallway. Herb’s leaning by the wall with a towel wrapped around his chest and another around his blonde locks.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jay struggles to come up with a sensible answer. Even after three months of living together, he has a lot of struggle seeing Herb naked — even partially.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It’s one A.M. You should sleep. We’re working early tomorrow.” Herb doesn’t even look at him twice. “Bip-bip.” He makes a shoo-shoo gesture with his hand. “Scuttle over. I want ice cream.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“The—” Jay clears his throat. “The fridge is right there; you can open it. Why should I move?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hey, just… Come on, do me a favour and scuttle over. What? Would you &lt;i&gt;die &lt;/i&gt;if you got more than a metre away from the kitchen?” Herb mumbles something under his breath, and Jay is pretty sure that it’s not a remark befitting of the twenty-first century.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Why would I need to—” Jay closes his eyes for a moment. Keep calm. Do not get into his game. “The fridge is right there.” He waves his hand towards it; he’s right, the fridge is plenty accessible, a good metre away from the sink. He really is &lt;i&gt;not&lt;/i&gt; in the way.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Acutely grasped, my friend.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Then, open it. Get your snack. Go to your room.” Simple as that.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Herb shakes his head and chuckles. “See, that won’t do, &lt;i&gt;mum.&lt;/i&gt; What you don’t understand is that I need &lt;i&gt;space&lt;/i&gt;. Eating ice cream at one A.M. is, like, an &lt;i&gt;art&lt;/i&gt;.” He closes the distance between them, punctuating each word with a step. “I want to get on the floor, lean on the counter, fridge door open to my side, and &lt;i&gt;savour&lt;/i&gt; that ice cream. Lick it, sigh happily, then lick it again, and smile. That’s how you eat ice cream at one A.M.” He steps back. “Now, be a good boy, move.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jay’s breathing picks up. He doesn’t understand. Why does Herb have to always, &lt;i&gt;always&lt;/i&gt;, make some sort of joke, some sort of argument, out of every little thing he says or does? Why does Herb have to smirk and look at him like he was some kind of idiot?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Come on. Move.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He should have listened to Willow. She warned him about Herb. That he is mean and chaotic. That working with him is one thing, but &lt;i&gt;living&lt;/i&gt; with him day to day is another totally. &lt;i&gt;‘im not sure youd be able to resist him more than a month tbhhhh so good luck lmaozihgbziefiqzef,’&lt;/i&gt; she texted him, and he should’ve listened.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hello?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And why couldn’t Herb leave him the fuck alone? He was in his zone, even if his zone was staring at a spoon. Maybe we should normalise spoon staring in our off-hours. Maybe sometimes, the most relaxing thing you can do is stare at a spoon. Can’t he get a single moment without being reminded of the existence of Herb?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Jesus, man. &lt;i&gt;Mooove.&lt;/i&gt;”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Oh, that’s it. He tenses up. He’s sick of Herb. Sick of the pointless debates in the middle of their shift, sick of his dirty little hands putting their mark on everything in their home, sick of all the smirks and smug looks. He can’t take it any more. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“FINE!” Jay yells and time stops.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Fuck. &lt;/i&gt;He hears his heart pumping blood to his face, his jaw, his brow, his nose. &lt;i&gt;Fuck, fuck, fuck. &lt;/i&gt;He’s breathing faster, clutching the counter. &lt;i&gt;That’s it, I’ve gone mad.&lt;/i&gt; And he doesn’t even move. Not yet. He can’t. He can’t because worry flashes in the other boy’s eyes for a second. &lt;i&gt;Fuck. &lt;/i&gt;Jay’s just as bad as Herb, isn’t he?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But it’s Herb, and Herb doesn’t know how to be anything other than a pest, so of course, of fucking course, he says, “Well, if you don’t move, I’ll have to lean on your lap.” Then he smiles again. “What a shame.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You— I— Fuck— Ugh.” Jay is almost panting at this point. He has to find some kind of witty answer, some kind of retort that would shut Herb off or make him laugh. Or both. But he’s panting and his head feels like a furnace and it’s one A.M and he’s been staring at a spoon for thirty minutes and he feels like he’s about to cry.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Oh god, he &lt;i&gt;is &lt;/i&gt;about to cry. Why is he about to cry?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He has no way out except running away.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;So that’s what he does. And he doesn’t even look back as he makes a beeline for the hallway. His room is just behind the corner.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Jay?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;Fuck.&lt;/i&gt; He picks up the pace but trips on something and almost falls over. Two blåhajs. One blue, one pink. Laying on the floor.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Perfect.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He wipes his tears one last time, picks the blue one, opens his room, locks his door, keels over, and holds on to the shark for dear life. And then he cries into its fur.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
