      <title>A.C.R.S.</title>
      <author> Lily_Rasputin </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/2140974/acrs/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2140974-acrs/chapter/2141021/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">55d02eeb5f412b26eeaac4f8c075f99514df35eb</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 28 Jan 2026 22:48:13 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;High School superstar quarterback, Kyle Patterson has a great arm, a gorgeous girlfriend, and a glorious future awaiting him. All of which gets jeopardized when he acquires Acute Chromosomal Recombination Syndrome and finds the physical changes are only the beginning.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2140974-acrs/chapter/2141021/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;A.C.R.S – Chapter 1&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The first sign that something was wrong was when I’d fainted at practice.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hadn’t felt well since waking up that morning, but I figured the brief flashes of fatigue, coupled with random bouts of gut-twisting nausea, were simply from the pressure of trying to lead my team to another state championship. After a rocky start at the beginning of the season, we’d finally found our rhythm, winning the next four games straight. Five more and we were guaranteed a top spot in the playoffs. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Hunched over behind Roman Merrick’s protruding ass with my hands between his legs, I burped in the middle of calling the play, sending a blast of foul-tasting bile surging up to the top of my throat. Grimacing, I forced it back down and managed to croak out the last word. Roman’s arms moved back to put the ball in my hands while the rest of the offensive line sprang into action.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hopped back two steps, ignoring the sloshing sensation taking place in my stomach, and looked downfield for an open receiver. The defense pushed to get through to stop me, but Roman, along with David Michaels, Lou Jones, and Steve Holland, gave me the necessary seconds to do what I needed to do.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Josh Hutchins, my best friend since the moment we crashed our bikes into each other’s the summer before fifth grade, waved one arm wildly as he sprinted laterally across the field about two dozen yards from the line of scrimmage. His coverage, Markus Dellinger, was a good six or seven steps behind him, leaving Josh wide open.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Drawing back my arm, I hurled the ball toward Josh just as a wave of vertigo slammed across me. The world pitched sharply to the left, and I suddenly found myself unable to remain upright. Darkness swallowed me whole, and the next thing I knew, I was lying on my back staring up at the mid-October afternoon sky, blinking through the fog clouding my brain.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A shrill whistle cut through the confused haze, and Roman’s grinning face appeared above me, holding out his hand.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What’s the matter, Kyle? You get sleepy?” His grin turned slightly lecherous. “If Kerri-Ann doesn’t stop keeping you up all night, Coach is gonna make you break up with her.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I took the offered assistance and let Roman pull me to my feet. The intense nausea still rolled through me, but I succeeded in remaining upright. I waited to see if the vertigo would return as well. When it didn’t, I forced a smile I didn’t feel on my face and shrugged one shoulder.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It’s not Kerri’s fault, Ro,” I said. “That throw was just so pretty it’s beauty made me swoon.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Maybe next time wait to see if Hutchins actually catches the damned thing first,” the gruff voice of Coach Costanza snarled from behind me. “And if you want to swoon, you can put in a transfer to join the cheerleaders.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Josh walked up, pulling off his helmet and shaking out his thick mane of dirty blonde hair as he grinned like a happy fool. “Kyle would like that too much, Coach. It would greatly increase his opportunities to put his hands on the body of a hot girl.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Coach’s twisted into a disappointed frown. “If you drop another easy pass, Hutchins, not only will you spend the one spending the rest of the season on the sidelines with the Raiderettes, you’ll also be dressed in their uniform.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I pulled off my own helmet, trying not to laugh at either Josh or Coach. Not that their banter, a staple of our practices, wasn’t funny. I just wasn’t completely sure that laughing wouldn’t lead to me barfing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Don’t do that to Josh, Coach,” Roman said as he winked at me. “We can’t win if everyone’s eyes are bleeding. The only way it could be worse is if it was Kyle.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I drew back my arm and punched my friend in the shoulder. “Speak for yourself, Bucko. I could rock a cheer skirt like nobody’s business.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Of course, you would, you fucking pussy,” Markus Dellinger said with a sneer as he walked past us. “You and Hutchins probably dress up in pink silk nighties before giving each other blow jobs.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Coach Costanza’s head swiveled in Marks’ direction, eyes narrowing at the hulking safety. “How about you worry less about your teammates and focus more on blocking to your left, Dellinger? Otherwise, you’ll be the one playing in a nightie.” Then he looked at the rest of us milling around. “That’s it, men. Gather up your gear and go home. We will go at it again tomorrow afternoon. Jones, make sure you rewrap that knee.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The rest of the team signaled their acknowledgment and began to move off the field toward the parking lot. Josh stayed next to me as Coach waited until everyone else was out of earshot. Then he turned to look at me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You sure you’re okay, Patterson? What happened?” The rough edge in his voice, the one he called his “Hardass Tone” was gone, replaced by genuine concern.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I wasn’t about to tell the man responsible for controlling my future that I’d fainted for no reason. So, I simply nodded and smiled. “I’m good, Coach. Promise. Just got a bit lightheaded for a moment, that’s all. Probably didn’t eat enoug