file folder. After a few seconds, he turned back to me, mouth folded down into a frown.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Kyle, you might have probably guessed what’s wrong with you, but before you let yourself go too far down that particular rabbit hole, I want to run a few tests and make sure. Does that sound okay?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I nodded, unable to speak.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He nodded in return and had his nurse come back to draw two vials of blood from my arm. Then he clapped his hand on my shoulder. “This shouldn’t take too long. At least not to rule out …” His fingers gave my shoulder a light squeeze. “Let’s just wait and see, okay?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He left the room, and the minutes ticked by slowly as I sat there alone. Though the exam room was chilly, my shivering was less tied to the temperature and more with trying not to freak out. If I didn’t have some crazy new form of cancer, which was what I was actually hoping, then the changes I was experiencing could only be A.C.R.S.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Meaning my life as I’d known it was over.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was somewhere between ten minutes and ten years before the door opened again. Doc Matthews, this time accompanied by my father, came in carrying a clipboard with pages and pages of printouts attached. My dad gave my shirtless chest the barest of glances before immediately looking away and taking up a spot right next to the table, arms crossed over his burly chest.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Doc Matthews looked down at the clipboard for a moment, then looked up to me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Kyle, it seems it is just as we suspected. You’ve developed Acute Chromosomal Recombination Syndrome.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I could only stare blankly at the man who’d been responsible for overseeing my health for the last seventeen years. It wasn’t that I hadn’t heard him clearly. It was more that my brain simply refused to accept the forgone prognosis.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Or the ramifications of it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My non-response must