      <title>Safe with You;— Back Home, Back to You</title>
      <author> Artemis98 </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/2113852/safe-with-you-back-home-back-to-you/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2113852-safe-with-you-back-home-back-to-you/chapter/2113917/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">1da8754f09014eaff288205978c980cec829867d</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 14 Jan 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Safe with You:&lt;br /&gt;    Back Home, Back to You&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;                                                                                                                  back-cover blurb&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Four years ago, Jamie Hayes left California and his best friend Lena behind. Four years in Chicago taught Jamie one thing: some kinds of lonely don't have a cure.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But California does. California has sun that doesn't feel suffocating. California has Lena Vance next door—best friend, fierce protector, the only person who's ever made Jamie feel safe. California has magical girl anime, League of Legends at 2 AM, and a Squad that might just have room for one more.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jamie's been wearing a costume that doesn't fit for as long as they can remember. Coming home might be the first step toward finding out what happens when she finally takes it off.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Current temporary cover was created by myself with a locally ran build of SD generating the base model which was finished manually using PS and IF on a drawing tablet.&lt;br /&gt; Artists are currently being commissioned to create art based on this setting which eventually includes a book cover.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/2113852-safe-with-you-back-home-back-to-you/chapter/2113917/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1: The Missing Piece&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;h1&gt;&lt;b&gt;Chapter 1: “The Missing Piece”&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/h1&gt; &lt;p&gt;July, 2014&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The California sun felt different than the sun in Chicago. In Chicago, the heat felt oppressive, like it was trying to trap you in the concrete. Here, as the Hayes family SUV finally turned onto the familiar pavement of the cul-de-sac, the heat felt like a blanket. It was golden and heavy, but for the first time in four years, the air didn’t feel like it was choking Jamie.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jamie sat in the backseat, knees pulled up to his chest, headphones on but playing nothing. He was sixteen now, though he felt a hundred years old inside.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The last four years had been a blur of gray skies and a crushing, silent loneliness. Chicago had been unkind. Jamie hadn’t made friends—not really. He had spent four years feeling like he was wearing a costume that didn’t fit, his skin itching with a wrongness he didn’t have the vocabulary to name yet. He had grown his hair out, hiding behind the brown, wavy curtain that now brushed his shoulders, and he had gotten thinner, retreating into oversized hoodies to hide a body that felt like a mistake.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He stared out the window as his dad parked the car. The house looked exactly the same. The lawn was green. The sprinkler system was ticking.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And right next door, the Vance house stood pristine and white.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jamie’s stomach twisted. &lt;i&gt;Four years.&lt;/i&gt; That was an eternity in high school time. They had been twelve when they left—children. Now they were juniors. Lena was probably different. His mom had told him Lena was “doing so well,” that she was captain of the cheer squad already, that she was beloved by the whole school.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;i&gt;She definitely has new friends,&lt;/i&gt; Jamie thought, a dark weight settling in his chest. &lt;i&gt;She probably has a boyfriend. She probably doesn’t want the weird, sad kid from next door clinging to her anymore.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We’re here, kiddo,” his dad said, killing the engine.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jamie took a shaky breath. He opened the car door and stepped out onto the driveway. He looked down at his shoes, Converse scuffed from pacing the floors of his bedroom in Chicago. He adjusted his hoodie, pulling the sleeves over his hands, trying to make himself smaller.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Then he heard the sound.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was the sound of a screen door being thrown open with enough force to bounce off the exterior wall. &lt;i&gt;Thwack.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jamie looked up.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Across the lawn, Lena Vance was standing on her porch. She was barefoot. She was wearing denim shorts and a simple tank top, her blonde hair pulled back in a ponytail that bobbed with her energy. She looked… radiant. Like she was made of the California sun itself. She was beautiful in a way that made Jamie’s chest ache, intimidated and awestruck all at once.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She didn’t wave. She didn’t smile politely. She didn’t wait for her parents.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“JAMIE!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The scream was raw, cracking in the middle. Lena leaped off the porch steps, skipping the walkway entirely and sprinting across the perfectly manicured grass separating their lawns.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jamie froze. He barely had time to brace himself before 5′7″ of solid muscle and momentum collided with him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It wasn’t a hug; it was an impact. Lena hit him with the force of a freight train, her arms wrapping around his neck, nearly knocking them both onto the asphalt. Jamie staggered back, his hands instinctively coming up to catch her waist to keep them upright.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You’re back,” she choked out, her face instantly buried in the crook of his neck. “You’re actually back.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She smelled like vanilla and something sharp, like ozone or static—a scent that was distinctly &lt;i&gt;Lena&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The breath rushed out of Jamie’s lungs, and with it, four years of tension. The “wrongness” that plagued him every day in Chicago didn’t vanish, but for the first time, it went quiet. The Lena-shaped hole in his heart, which had been bleeding a slow, miserable ache since he was twelve, suddenly plugged itself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hi, Lele,” Jamie whispered, his voice cracking. He squeezed his eyes shut, burying his face in her shoulder, gripping the back of her shirt so hard his knuckles turned white.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They stood there in the driveway for a long time. The Hayes parents and the Vance parents were coming out now, exchanging greetings, laughing, pointing at the two teenagers locked in a death grip. But Lena didn’t let go. She was trembling. Jamie realized, with a shock, that she was crying.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Don’t you ever leave again,” she hissed into his neck, her voice wet and fierce. “I swear to God, Jamie, if you move again, I’m locking you up in the basement”.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jamie let out a wet, shaky laugh. “Okay.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Lena finally pulled back, just an inch, to look at him. Her hands came up to cup his face, squishing his cheeks. She scanned him intensely—taking in the longer hair, the delicate features, the sadness that was still lingering in his green eyes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You got pretty,” she stated, her tone matter-of-fact, though her eyes were red-rimmed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jamie flushed, looking away. “I… I just grew my hair out. I can cut it if it’s—”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Don’t you dare,” Lena interrupted, her thumbs brushing under his eyes, wiping away a tear he hadn’t realized had fallen. “I love it. You look like a prince.” She paused, then corrected herself with a soft, watery smile. “No. Like a princess. My princess.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was an old nickname, a private joke from when they were ten and Jamie had played the princess in a pretend tower. Hearing it now, used with such unironic affection, made Jamie’s knees weak.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Come on,” Lena said, grabbing his hand. She didn’t ask if he wanted to say hi to his parents. She didn’t ask if he wanted to unpack. She just started dragging him toward her house. “You’re coming with me.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“My bags…” Jamie started feebly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Dad will get them!” Lena yelled over her shoulder without stopping.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Mr. Vance, standing by the garage, just saluted. “I got it! Go on, you two!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Lena dragged Jamie up the porch, through the cool, air-conditioned hallway of the Vance house—which smelled exactly like it used to, lemon polish and fresh linen—and up the stairs to her bedroom.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She kicked the door shut behind them, closing out the world.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jamie looked around, expecting the pink, fluffy room of their childhood. He blinked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The room was still unmistakably Lena’s, but it had evolved. One wall was dominated by a desk that looked like the cockpit of a spaceship. A massive, sleek white PC tower hummed with soft blue LED lights. Three monitors were mounted on arms. A headset that looked expensive enough to buy a used car sat on a white mechanical keyboard.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You… you play now?” Jamie asked, bewildered, staring at the setup.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“League of Legends,” Lena muttered, kicking off her shorts to change into sweatpants right in front of him, completely unbothered. “I needed to kill things. It helped with the stress.” She tossed Jamie a pair of her own gray sweatpants—they were oversized on her, which meant they’d fit him perfectly. “Put these on. Those jeans look uncomfortable.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jamie obeyed, turning his back shyly to change. When he turned back around, Lena was already in her bed—a massive, plush thing piled high with pillows. She patted the empty space beside her.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Get in.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jamie climbed in. The sheets were cool and soft. He hesitated, lying on his back, staring at the ceiling. He felt stiff, the anxiety of the last few years still ghosting over his skin. &lt;i&gt;What do I do? Do we talk? Does she want to hear about Chicago?&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He felt an arm snake around his waist.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Lena scooted close, pressing her chest against his back, her chin hooking over his shoulder. She pulled him flush against her, her leg hooking over his legs, trapping him. She effectively turned herself into a human shield, shielding him from the world, from Chicago, from everything.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I missed you so much it made me physically sick,” Lena whispered into his ear, her voice devoid of the confident, popular cheerleader tone she used outside. It was just Lena. “I tried to be nice to everyone, and I have all these ‘friends’ now, and they’re great, I guess… but god, Jamie. It was so lonely.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Jamie’s breath hitched. He turned his head slightly into the pillow, his hand coming up to hold the arm she had wrapped around him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I didn’t have anyone,” Jamie admitted, his voice barely audible. “I just… I stayed in my room. I missed you every day.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Lena tightened her grip, pulling him closer if that was even possible. She buried her face in his hair, inhaling deeply.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We’re fixing it,” she declared, her voice muffled by his hair. “We’re going to fix it. You’re staying here. We’re going to eat snacks, and I’m going to show you my kill-death ratio, which is frankly disgusting, and you’re going to sleep. You look like you haven’t slept in four years.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I haven’t,” Jamie mumbled, his eyelids already feeling heavy. The safety of her warmth was acting like a sedative.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sleep,” Lena commanded softly, pressing a kiss to the back of his neck. “I’ve got you.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And for the first time since 2010, Jamie Hayes closed his eyes and felt safe.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
